# Recording & documenting a page's API flow

When the user asks to **record, analyze, or document the API / network flow** of a web
page or app module — phrasings like "what APIs does this page call", "document the
checkout flow", "track the requests on this screen", "map the API calls" — you MUST use
the **`browser-flow-tracker` MCP tools**. This is the only approved method.

## Do

- Use `mcp_browser-flow-tracker_start_tracking` to begin. It launches a fresh browser
  window (or attaches to one) and **auto-selects a free debug port** — you do not manage
  ports.
- Then **STOP and let the USER navigate the flow themselves.** The capture is
  user-driven. Post a short instruction telling them to click through the real flow in
  the open window and say "done" when finished.
- Use `mcp_browser-flow-tracker_get_flow` for a live peek without stopping.
- When the user says they are done, call `mcp_browser-flow-tracker_stop_tracking` (pass a
  `name` and `title`). It writes `.flow.json`, `.har`, and `.md` files. Read the
  `.flow.json` from disk and write the user a clean flow document from it.

## Do NOT

- Do NOT launch browsers, kill processes, or poke at `--remote-debugging-port` / port
  9222 via the shell. `start_tracking` handles all of that.
- Do NOT write your own network-sniffing scripts or try to analyze traffic yourself.
- Do NOT auto-navigate or click through the flow on the user's behalf — they drive.
- Do NOT use headless mode unless the user asks; they need to see and interact with the
  window (and log in).

## Notes

- The launched window uses a **persistent profile**, so a login done once is remembered
  on later recordings. For flows behind auth, the user just logs in the first time.
- If `stop_tracking`'s result is too large to return inline, read the written
  `.flow.json` file from disk instead and summarize from there.
